</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[90,1141,3097,3122]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="180.[90,1296,3097,3477]" box="[90,1141,3097,3122]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[90,246,3097,3122]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Thomas, 1902" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1902" box="[258,773,3097,3122]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Mus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="sylvaticus" subSpecies="witherbyi">Mus sylvaticus witherbyi Thomas, 1902</taxonomicName>
, Shul, Fars Province, Iran.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="180" pageNumber="783" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="180.[90,1296,3097,3477]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[91,342,3128,3162]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="witherbyi">Apodemus witherbyi</taxonomicName>
has complex taxonomic history. It was originally described as a sub-species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[234,395,3167,3201]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Mus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sylvaticus">A. sylvaticus</taxonomicName>
, but morphological and genetic analyses distinguished it, under name 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blanford" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[178,318,3207,3241]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arianus">A. arianus</taxonomicName>
, from previously described taxa (such as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ognev" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[895,1071,3207,3241]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fulvipectus">A. fulvipectus</taxonomicName>
, A. falzfeini, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Filippucci, Simson &amp; Nevo" authorityYear="1989" box="[91,293,3255,3280]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hermonensis">A. hermonensis</taxonomicName>
); holotype of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blanford" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[496,638,3255,3280]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arianus">A. arianus</taxonomicName>
, however, corresponds to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melchior" authorityYear="1834" box="[1016,1180,3255,3280]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Mus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="flavicollis">A. flavicollis</taxonomicName>
, so that name witherby: must be used. B. Krystufek and V. Vohralik in 2009 redefined morphoanatomical characters of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[456,611,3325,3359]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="witherbyi">A. witherbyi</taxonomicName>
compared with A. wralensis for Turkish populations, and Z. Mohammadi and colleagues in 2014 compared them with A. ponticusfor Iranian ones. Molecular phylogeny ofJ. Darvish and colleagues in 2015 showed that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[91,244,3443,3477]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="witherbyi">A. witherbyi</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName box="[469,600,3443,3477]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Sylvaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Sylvaemus</taxonomicName>
group and is sister taxon of subclade containing
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="180.[1976,2583,296,716]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pallas" baseAuthorityYear="1811" box="[1976,2129,296,321]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="uralensis">A. uralensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melchior" authorityYear="1834" box="[2145,2306,296,321]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Mus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="flavicollis">A. flavicollis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sviridenko" baseAuthorityYear="1936" box="[2321,2467,296,321]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ponticus">A. ponticus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barrett-Hamilton" authorityYear="1900" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pallipes">A. pallipes</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vorontsov, Boyeskorov &amp; Mezhzherin" authorityYear="1992" box="[2108,2282,331,360]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hyrcanicus">A. hyrcanicus</taxonomicName>
. This species also incudes the recently described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Darvish, Javidkar &amp; Siahsarvie" authorityYear="2006" box="[2382,2583,367,401]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Apodemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="avicennicus">A. avicennicus</taxonomicName>
based on genetic data. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="180" pageNumber="783" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6888020" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6888020" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6888020/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" startId="180.[1976,2148,445,479]" targetBox="[1361,1953,299,714]" targetPageId="180">
<paragraph blockId="180.[1976,2583,296,716]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1976,2152,445,479]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">Distribution.</emphasis>
SE Ukraine (E of Dnieper River), S European Russia, Greece (E Aegean Is of Kos and Rhodes), Turkey (Anatolia), Syria, Lebanon, Israel, NW Jordan, Georgia, Armenia, Azerbaijan, N Iran, and &amp; § Turkmenistan.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="180" pageNumber="783" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="180.[1976,2583,296,716]" lastBlockId="180.[1362,2570,730,1505]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1976,2262,682,716]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 77-110 mm, tail 75-118 mm, ear 14-18 mm, hindfoot 19-24 mm; weight 16-34 g. The Steppe Field Mouse is medium sized and slender. Dorsal pelage yellowish-brown to wood-brown, sharply delimited white underparts. Tail is bicolored, equal or slightly longer (c.103%) than head-body. Chromosomal complement has 2n = 48, FNa = 46.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="180" pageNumber="783" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="180.[1362,2570,730,1505]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1363,1475,879,913]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">Habitat.</emphasis>
The Steppe Field Mouse can live in wide variety of environments. In Turkey it has been found both in open habitats and in cedar forests, as well as in shrublands and degraded forest. It needs shrub cover as well as some rocky areas in open grasslands (
<taxonomicName box="[1376,1500,1001,1030]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Artemisia</taxonomicName>
[
<taxonomicName box="[1521,1675,1001,1030]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
] — 
<taxonomicName box="[1717,1805,1001,1030]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Pistacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Pistacia</taxonomicName>
[
<taxonomicName box="[1825,2041,1001,1030]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Anacardiaceae</taxonomicName>
], Amygdalus [
<taxonomicName box="[2226,2357,1001,1030]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
| steppes) and is found at up to 2800 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="180" pageNumber="783" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="180.[1362,2570,730,1505]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1364,1629,1076,1110]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
The Steppe Field Mouse is an omnivorous species, but food consists predominantly of seeds and acorns, followed by fruits, flowers, stems, mushrooms, insects, snails, and earthworms, all theses in variable proportions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="180" pageNumber="783" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="180.[1362,2570,730,1505]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1364,1498,1199,1228]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">Breeding.</emphasis>
Reproduction may be more common in spring and summer. Litter size, estimated from numbers of embryos and placental scars, is 1-7 (average 4-5).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1362,2277,1273,1307]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="180.[1362,2570,730,1505]" box="[1362,2277,1273,1307]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1362,1598,1273,1307]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Steppe Field Mice are nocturnal and terrestrial.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1364,2304,1313,1347]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="180.[1362,2570,730,1505]" box="[1364,2304,1313,1347]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1364,2065,1313,1347]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1364,2416,1352,1386]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="180.[1362,2570,730,1505]" box="[1364,2416,1352,1386]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1364,1713,1352,1386]" pageId="180" pageNumber="783">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red Last.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
